[2
Date: Tue, 15 Jun 1999 08:18:36 EDT
From: *Ed Regis, Ph.D* <edregis@aol.com

The island in question is Gruinard Island, located one-half mile off
the northwest coast of Scotland. The British government exploded
anthrax bombs on Gruinard not during WWI but during the summers
of 1942 and 1943. In 1986, a group from CDE [Chemical Defense
Establishment, Porton Down, successfully decontaminated Gruinard
Island with a mixture of five percent formaldehyde, a sporicidal chemical,
in sea water. On April 24, 1990, the British Under Secretary of State
for Defense came to Gruinard and formally declared the island "fit for
habitation by man and beast."
Although the island is not inhabited, it is no longer contaminated by
anthrax spores.
Refs:
Manchee, R. J. et al. "Bacillus anthracis on Gruinard Island." Nature.
Vol 294 (19 November 1981): 254-255.
"Decontamination of Bacillus anthracis on Gruinard Island?" Nature.
Vol. 303 (19 May 1983): 239-240.
Pearson, Graham S. "Gruinard Island Returns to Civil Use." The ASA
Newsletter 90-5. (October 1990).
---
Ed Regis, Ph.D.
College Fellow
Western Maryland College
Westminster, Maryland 21157
edregis@aol.com
